<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-07-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-07-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="99" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d99">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/10104</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-07-13"><hi rend="italic">July 13,
                                1928</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 914</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your despatch
                            No. 1511, dated May 22, 1928, regarding a request made to you through an
                            official of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs that you use your efforts
                            with the Southern authorities to persuade them to respond to the appeal
                            for peace of Chang Tso-lin. The reply which you caused to be sent to
                            this request meets with the approval of the Department.</p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Frank B. Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>